      "SummaryText": "RISK MANAGEMENT PLAN EXECUTIVE SUMMARY\nThe Executive Summary of the RMP gives an overview of each of the components of the Risk Management Program, including:\n\u0095\tA narrative on the accidental release prevention and emergency response policies as required by 40 CFR 68.155(a);\n\u0095\tA description of the stationary source and regulated substances handled as required by 40 CFR 68.155(b);\n\u0095\tA section on general accidental release prevention and chemical-specific prevention steps as required by 40 CFR 68.155(c);\n\u0095\tFive-Year Accident History of the facility as required by 40 CFR 68.155(d);\n\u0095\tA description of the emergency response program as required by 40 CFR 68.155(e); and\n\u0095\tA discussion of planned changes to improve safety as required by 40 CFR 68.155(f).  \n\nThe Executive Summary no longer includes a discussion of the Worst-Case and Alternative Release Scenarios reported to the EPA due to regulations promulgated on April 9, 2004 (40 CFR 68.155 requirements were revised per Federal Register Document 04-5877).\nThe Executive Summary included in RMP*eSubmit is shown in its entirety below.\n\nINTRODUCTION AND POLICIES\nSABIC Innovative Plastics \u0096 Bay St. Louis Facility (SABIC) is committed to managing all operations in a manner that protects the environment and the health and safety of employees, customers, contractors, and the public while fully complying with applicable laws and regulations. SABIC\u0092s management philosophy goals are achieved through the implementation of its Environmental, Health, Safety and Process Safety Management Systems, by the personal commitments of employees and contractors, and by open communication with employees, customers, neighbors, and regulators. \n\nThe purpose of this Risk Management Plan is to provide information about operations at the facility, programs to prevent accidental chemical releases, emergency response plans in the event of an accidental release, the five-year accident history of the facility and planned changes to improve safety at the p"
    },
    {
      "ESSeqNum": 1,
      "FacilityID": 1000115111,
      "SummaryText": "lant.\n\nSTATIONARY SOURCE AND REGULATED SUBSTANCES\nThe Bay St. Louis Facility is operated by SABIC US Holdings LP and processes acrylonitrile and styrene to produce acrylonitrile-butadiene-styrene (ABS), styrene-acrylonitrile (SAN), and other plastic resins. \n\nThe facility consists of 3 covered processes, the AN Unloading Storage, SAN Production Lines, and the ABS Production Lines processes.\n\nThere is one EPA RMP regulated toxic chemical used at the facility.  Acrylonitrile is the only RMP regulated toxic material present in amounts greater than the threshold quantity.  There are no RMP regulated flammable materials present as pure components, or in mixtures, in amounts greater than the threshold quantities, that are used or stored at the SABIC facility. The facility\u0092s covered processes meet Program Level Three requirements.\n\nACCIDENTAL RELEASE PREVENTION AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE POLICIES\nThe accidental release prevention and emergency response programs in place at the facility are part of the high standards striven for by SABIC.   These high standards include: \n\u0095\tOperating in compliance with required environmental permits and regulations. \n\u0095\tOperating and maintaining the assets in such a manner that the risk of unintentional releases are minimized.\n\u0095\tOperating and maintaining assets in such a manner that promotes the health and safety of all employees, contractors , and visitors. \n\u0095\tCorrecting non-compliance found by regular audits of the facility.\nThe outstanding safety programs at the Bay St. Louis facility have earned OSHA Voluntary Protection Program (VPP) STAR status, presented by the Occupational Safety and Health Administration for exemplary safety management. This is OSHA\u0092s highest recognition for safety performance. This OSHA Program includes agency revalidation audits every 3-5 years. The Bay St. Louis facility has been an OSHA VPP Star site since 1993, with the most recent OSHA program review in March 2023.\n\nPREVENTION PROGRAM\nThe SABIC Facility is operatin"
    },
