      "SummaryText": "g under the standards of the Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) Process Safety Management (PSM) Program.  Management and employee commitment to ongoing analysis of the potential hazards of the process, detailed training, and emphasis on safety have all helped prevent serious chemical release accidents over the last 5 years.  Part of this program has also involved identifying and taking steps to reduce the risk of potential accidental chemical releases.  A few examples of the prevention features implemented at this facility include:\n\u0095\tComputer-controlled safety systems on their chemical reaction vessels to ensure that any deviations from the intended operating conditions are immediately identified and corrected.\n\u0095\tSafety procedures that reduce the potential for human error which could lead to storage tank overfill.\n\u0095\tSecondary containment dikes around storage tanks to contain a spill.\n\u0095\tSpill containment around unloading stations to mitigate the impact of a leak.\n\u0095\tExtensive safety information about the processes available to employees.\n\u0095\tWritten operating procedures that include emergency response actions.\n\u0095\tComprehensive employee and contractor training programs to promote consistently safe work practices.\n\u0095\tPreventive maintenance and testing of vessels through the Mechanical Integrity program helps to ensure that structural failures do not occur in process equipment.\n\u0095\tSafety procedure to review proposed plant modifications before they are implemented for possible hazards (Management of Change).\n\u0095\tSafety pre-qualification for all contractors.\n\u0095\tSafety reviews prior to startup of all processes.\n\u0095\tSafety permitting procedures that control hazards during special operations such as welding (Hot Work) and other maintenance activities.\n\nFIVE-YEAR ACCIDENT HISTORY\nWithin the last five years, there have been no releases of RMP Regulated Substances that resulted in onsite injuries, death or property damage or any offsite impacts.\n\nEMERGENCY RESPONSE PROGR"
    },
